{{notability|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Henrik Palmgren | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Kungälv]], [[Västra Götaland County|Västra Götalands län]], [[Sweden]]<ref name="Englund" /> | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Swedes|Swedish]] | other_names = | occupation = [[Podcast]]er, [[Video blog|vlogger]], [[YouTube]] personality | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | spouse = [[Lana Lokteff]]<ref name=NPR>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Emma|last2=Stewart|first2=Ian|title=The Women Behind The 'Alt-Right'|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/20/544134546/the-women-behind-the-alt-right|accessdate=May 7, 2018|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=August 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref> }}
'''Henrik Palmgren''' is a Swedish [[alt-right]] political podcaster, vlogger, and YouTube personality.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/How-a-Student-Got-Kicked-Out/243549?key=tsxY_TWHW8qXB5a8zx2fCjFExZG2KdHSQXc_HzXGIWAjv9GyiV4kS55e30fdGFBoQ09JWTdBSXNjaGVzb0tkUnAycjdtLWRaRGR3cjdQUUVxNlB1Y2pfYkZkWQ|title=How a Student Got Kicked Out of Class — and Became a Conservative Hero|date=2018-05-31|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> He founded the alt-right website ''Red Ice'' in 2003.<ref name=":0" />
== Career == Palmgren launched the company Red Ice in 2002 in Gothenburg, Sweden as an outlet for [[conspiracy theories]] about [[Unidentified flying object|U.F.O.]]s, [[Masonic conspiracy theories|Freemasonry]], [[9/11 conspiracy theories|9/11]], and [[New World Order (conspiracy theory)|The Illuminati]].<ref name="darby-2">{{cite news |last1=Darby |first1=Seyward |title=The Rise of the Valkyries |url=https://harpers.org/archive/2017/09/the-rise-of-the-valkyries/2/ |accessdate=18 September 2018 |work=Harper's Magazine |date=September 2017 |page=2}}</ref> In 2008 he began collaborating with [[Lana Lokteff]], an Oregon-based musician who was a listener to his internet radio show. They married in 2011.<ref name="darby-8">{{cite news |last1=Darby |first1=Seyward |title=The Rise of the Valkyries |url=https://harpers.org/archive/2017/09/the-rise-of-the-valkyries/8/ |accessdate=18 September 2018 |work=Harper's Magazine |date=September 2017 |page=8}}</ref> Beginning in 2012, Red Ice started shifting towards more racist conspiracy theories, such as the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]] and [[Holocaust denial]].<ref name="darby-2"/>
Palmgren is the host of the podcast and video program ''Red Ice Radio'', while Lokteff hosts ''Radio 3Fourteen''.<ref name=NPR/> Palmgren's program includes content promoting [[white nationalism]], [[anti-Semitism]], [[paranormal]] topics, holocaust revisionism, and [[far-right politics]].<ref name="darby-2"/> Palmgren's show has included guests such as [[Ingrid Carlqvist]], [[Richard B. Spencer]], [[Kevin B. MacDonald]], [[David Duke]], [[Michael A. Hoffman II]], [[Gilad Atzmon]], [[David Icke]], [[Faith Goldy]], [[Mark Collett]], [[Jim Fetzer]], [[Paul Nehlen]], [[Andrew Anglin]], [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] prospective Member of Parliament, Jack Sen, and [[Millennial Woes]], among many others.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
In May 2017, ''[[The Forward]]'' reported that Palmgren is collaborating with white nationalist [[Richard B. Spencer]] to form a new media company.<ref>Kestenbaum, Sam (May 3, 2017). [http://forward.com/fast-forward/370870/white-nationalist-richard-spencer-makes-alt-right-expansion-in-sweden/ White Nationalist Richard Spencer Makes ‘Alt-Right’ Expansion In Sweden], [[The Forward]].</ref>
Palmgren took part in the [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]].<ref name="Englund">Englund, Tindra (14 August 2017) [http://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/svenska-hogerextremister-pa-plats-i-charlottesville/ Svenska högerextremister på plats i Charlottesville]. In: [[Dagens Nyheter]] (in Swedish).{{subscription required}}</ref>
In July 2018, Palmgren and Lotkeff, alongside several other alt-right figures including Goldy, were banned from the online money transfer service [[PayPal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/paypal-kicks-yet-more-white-nationalists-off-its-funding-site-6f359b586f72/|title=3 more prominent far-right accounts get de-platformed by PayPal|access-date=2018-09-18|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Personal life == Originally from [[Kungälv]], Palmgren has lived in [[Oregon]] for many years.<ref name="Englund" /> He is married to Lana Lokteff who is associated with the [[alt-right]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate|title=From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2017-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Teacher Who Hosted Far-Right Podcast Encouraging White Nationalists To Infiltrate Schools Resigns|author=Palmer, Ewan|date=April 3, 2018|url=http://www.newsweek.com/florida-teacher-who-hosted-far-right-podcast-encouraging-white-nationalists-869126|work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref>
