'''Hukam''' ({{lang-pa| ਹੁਕਮਿ}}) is a [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] word derived from the [[Arabic language|Arabic]] ''[[hukm]]'', meaning "command" or "divine order."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YOI1nB_zTyAC&pg=PA49&dq=Hukam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiApNqc3q3QAhUH5oMKHTN1BtQQ6AEIMjAE#v=onepage&q=Hukam&f=false|title=Sikhism|last=Haar|first=Kristen|last2=Kalsi|first2=Sewa Singh|date=2009-01-01|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438106472|language=en}}</ref> In Sikhism, Hukam represents the goal of becoming in harmony with the will of God and thus attaining inner peace.  It also designates the practice of opening up at random to a page in the Sikh scripture (Guru Granth Sahib) to receive God's guidance on how to handle a certain situation, as answer to a question, or as more general guidance for that day.
